snippet.textDisplay:
This reminds me a lot of a recent 3Blue1Brown video: https://youtu.be/EK32jo7i5LQ
I'm very much not a math person, but to my stupid brain it looks like:
-Both start with a seemingly simple formula that create more complex patterns then they have any right to.
-Both of those formulas build on themselves (the output of one step is in input for the next)
-Both have some factor that stops them from simply going infinite (here the (1-x), in the 3Brown1Blue video it's the fact that the lines goes in a circle, so every 2pi, the whole thing is back at 0)
-Both have the crucial feature that a full "cycle" doesn't neatly fit on the constraints the limiting factor creates: there is always a bit left, like the remainder in a division.
This remainder stays in the system, compounding, interacting with itself and the rest of the formula.
Sooooo, something something prime numbers?

snippet.textDisplay:
This is a great video to show how familiar phenomena are connected via math, both simple and complex. I didn't even thought the Mandelbrot set had simple solutions in some planes, even though I had heard of period-doubling bifurcation in some context.

I am particularly thrilled that I can observe this phenomenon on my faucet, and record slow-mo with a phone camera! The premise, however, is a little misleading. Water dripping from faucet is not really driven by constant pressure through constant constriction. If that, there wouldn't be any bifurcation. The main interaction is among gravity (constant), surface tension (extremely dynamic as water goes through shape change), and Van der Waals force (also extremely dynamic as water change shape).
snippet.textOriginal:
This is a great video to show how familiar phenomena are connected via math, both simple and complex. I didn't even thought the Mandelbrot set had simple solutions in some planes, even though I had heard of period-doubling bifurcation in some context.

I am particularly thrilled that I can observe this phenomenon on my faucet, and record slow-mo with a phone camera!  The premise, however, is a little misleading.  Water dripping from faucet is not really driven by constant pressure through constant constriction.  If that, there wouldn't be any bifurcation.  The main interaction is among gravity (constant), surface tension (extremely dynamic as water goes through shape change), and Van der Waals force (also extremely dynamic as water change shape).
